            <span id="ChapterParagraphTwo">
                    I entered VMH and our first dorm was the old one behind the hospital. My first roommate was Glenys Maddox. The name of the dorm was Blackford Hall. We lived there until the new dorms across the street from the hospital were built. We had classes from four to six hours each day and we were on duty in the hospital for four hours as well. We most often had split shifts in the hospital, working four hours in the a.m. and then four hours in the evening or vice versa.
            </span>
            
            <span id="SEE_MORE"><a href="#" id="restofstory1-show"  onclick="showHide('restofstory1');return false;">SEE MORE</a>
            </span>

            <div id="restofstory1" class="more">
                <span id="ChapterParagraphTwo">
                    My second roommate was Carol Muckleston. We developed a remarkable friendship which has lasted for 61 years—at this writing, we still write to each other to keep in touch even though we haven’t seen each other for about 40 years! I was able to go out to Ruby’s home quite often when off duty; I loved to go out to be with her and Jack and Ken. They were great nephews and fun to be with. Ruby would come and meet me and we would go strolling down the streets of Seattle and wonder at all the sights of the big city. <br /><br />

                    The theaters were awesome—huge—and so many people! The Pike Street Market was a fun place to visit. Also going down to Lake Washington and maybe taking a ferry ride across or even a bus across the swinging bridge, all that was quite an adventure for a girl from small-time Idaho! I dated a few nice fellows while in training…Chuck…can’t remember his last name. Dick Small was a real gentleman and he brought me flowers very frequently, roses mostly. And John Greenwalt was very special. I would probably have gone back to Seattle and married him if Ken hadn’t come along. He was a good man but not a member of the church and as I think back it would have been a drastic mistake for me to have done that. And Kenneth Bird was a very effective persuader! <br /><br />

                    We had lots of fun get-togethers among the nursing students; we went on picnics and to a lot of movies in those years. I remember the capping ceremony, also graduation, when we received our long sleeved white uniforms. Only registered nurses could wear a long-sleeved uniform! We also had reciprocity sections when we left VMH and went to other hospitals for specialized training. I trained Children’s Orthopedic Hospital and Steilacoom Psychiatric Hospital south of Seattle in Steilacoom. <br /><br />

                    I remember there being a huge veggie garden near by Steilacoom and we students without dates sometimes would sneak down there to the garden and eat strawberries; they were huge and beautiful and irresistible. I also remember being sunburned severely from being either at the lake or at the beach for too long…oooooh…I can still remember one of the girls rubbing my red hot back with lotion to soothe the pain. During vacation time each year, I rode the bus back home to Idaho Falls alone; never had any fear even though it was during the war.<br /><br /> 

                    I became quite a bus rider! During one year of training, my best friend Donna Cook, from Idaho Falls, came over for a visit because her boyfriend Arland Rasmussen was in the Navy and stationed there and we went out there to see him. They later married. Also my first boyfriend Roy Gardner, also from Idaho Falls and a neighbor on 16th Street, was in the Navy and stationed in the same area—I have many memories in my mind about those years in Seattle. They are special and treasured memories. <br /><br />

                    I can bring up the feelings of riding the huge electric buses from downtown out to Ruby’s, her home on Alamo Place, then back to the hospital riding the bus and hearing the conductor crying out the names of the streets where the bus stopped…I even remember the name of one of them…“Jackson Street.” I graduated from VMH in August of 1947. <br /><br />

                    My parents drove over to pick me up and especially to see little Mike, the little boy that was born just before I graduated. Ruby wanted a girl but Mike has been so special. Her three boys have always been very special to me because of those years when we were so close. When I returned to Idaho Falls, I was able to obtain a position as office nurse for Dr. Walter R. West, a “hometown” doctor. Also working in the office was Donna, as secretary and receptionist and Mary Mcintire who was the chief nurse. I worked for the doctor for a year and a half before marrying Ken. I was able to use much of my training and even learned to take and develop x-rays. I worked for the doctor until we moved out to the farm in Milo. Dr. West delivered Michael, Marlon, Robert, and Debra, while Randy and Janet were delivered by Dr. Carey. He worked with a certain client on advertisements that made him quite a bit of money. Then he started working with restaurants, in helping them design advertisements, and create illustrations. 
                </span>

